    <div class="wrap">
      <h2>Common Master-Bilt failures — panel seals, DD/DC compressor, door heaters</h2>
      <p class="intro">
        Pattern recognition is what keeps the labor bill reasonable. On Master-Bilt equipment the failures cluster in a
        few predictable zones — freezer-door heaters, dipping cabinet compressors, panel seams on older builds, and the
        refrigeration side on walk-ins that have been running LA summers for a decade or more.
      </p>

      <div class="fail-block">
        <h3>DD-series dipping cabinet compressor running hot</h3>
        <p>
          The ice cream starts softening at the back corners, the front of the cabinet sounds louder than it used to,
          and in summer the compressor is cycling long or not shutting off. Nine times out of ten the root cause isn't
          the compressor itself — it's a condenser coil packed with dust, bakery flour, or the shop's air is simply
          choked. We pull the service panel, brush and vacuum the coil, check the fan-motor amp draw, and retest. If the
          coil is clean and the compressor is still discharging hot, we move to refrigerant charge and then the compressor
          itself. Honest call from our techs: if the cabinet is 12-plus years old and the compressor is the original
          hermetic, swap it — parts cost chases labor cost otherwise.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fail-block">
        <h3>Freezer-door heater element failure — ice building around the door frame</h3>
        <p>
          On Master-Bilt freezer-side walk-ins, the door frame runs a resistance heater that keeps condensation and ice
          off the gasket contact surface. When the heater drops out, you see frost creeping down the outside edge of the
          door within a day, then a ridge of ice that breaks the gasket seal and makes the problem cascade — the freezer
          works harder, the compressor runs longer, and the ice gets worse. We meter the element for continuity, trace
          back to the junction box (where LA kitchen humidity corrodes terminals within a few years), and either replace
          the element or clean up the connection if that's all it is. Quick job when the part is on the truck.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fail-block">
        <h3>Panel-seam separation on older walk-ins — rooftop or forklift stress</h3>
        <p>
          On Master-Bilt walk-ins over fifteen years old we occasionally see a hairline separation at a ceiling or
          vertical panel seam. Two usual causes: rooftop HVAC work above the walk-in where the cam-locks flexed, or a
          forklift strike on a side wall during a restaurant reno. Shows up as a thin rime of frost tracking along a
          seam from inside the box. Caulk alone won't fix a seam that's actually moved — we check panel alignment first,
          re-tighten cam-locks if they've loosened, and then seal with NSF food-zone silicone. If the panels are
          out-of-square, we tell you straight: a panel pull-and-reset is the right fix, not another caulk pass.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fail-block">
        <h3>Walk-in condensing-unit fan motor down after a heat wave</h3>
        <p>
          Rooftop Master-Bilt condensing units take a beating during an LA heat wave. The condenser fan runs continuously
          for two or three 100-degree days, the motor bearings give out, and the compressor then over-pressures and
          trips on high-head safety. We show up to what the restaurant thinks is a dead compressor and trace it
          backward — the fan motor is the root cause, the compressor protected itself. Fan motor swap in common sizes
          on the truck, condenser coil cleaned of grease and dust while we're up there, high-pressure switch verified,
          system restarted. Compressor usually survives.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fail-block">
        <h3>Evaporator defrost stuck — ice slab on the coil</h3>
        <p>
          On Master-Bilt freezer walk-ins the evaporator runs a defrost sequence on a timer or demand control. When the
          sequence stops working, ice builds on the coil, airflow chokes, and the freezer starts drifting warm even though
          the compressor is running hard. Usual suspects on older installs: failed defrost termination thermostat, burned
          defrost heater, or a mechanical timer that lost its program. On newer installs we check the defrost contactor
          and controller. We pull the ice down with a steam kettle — chisels kill aluminum coils — verify defrost runs
          end to end, and swap the component that failed.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fail-block">
        <h3>DD dipping cabinet thermostat drift — ice cream too soft or frozen solid</h3>
        <p>
          A DD cabinet that's been running for a decade will eventually show thermostat drift. Symptoms split two ways:
          ice cream softens at the back during service because the thermostat is letting the cabinet climb above spec,
          or the product is freezer-burned hard because the thermostat is running too cold. We test the bulb, verify the
          setpoint against a calibrated thermometer at the product zone, and either re-calibrate or replace. Older
          mechanical thermostats are straight swaps; newer electronic controls sometimes just need a firmware-level reset
          through the service menu.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

