      <p>
        Master-Bilt was acquired as part of the Ali Group North America / Welbilt transaction in July 2022. That
        consolidation moved Master-Bilt into the same parent family as Kolpak (panel walk-ins), Nor-Lake (walk-ins and
        Scientific refrigeration), Champion (commercial dishwashers), Beverage-Air (reach-in refrigeration), Manitowoc
        (ice machines), and Garland (cooking). Most SERP content still describes Master-Bilt as Welbilt-owned — that's
        out of date as of 2022 and we mention it on every call where the owner is confused about which vendor supplies
        parts.
      </p>
      <p>
        The practical effect for an LA restaurant: the Master-Bilt parts channel is now part of the Ali distribution
        network, which for a kitchen running a mixed Ali fleet (say, a Master-Bilt walk-in plus a Kolpak reach-in plus
        a Champion dishwasher plus a Manitowoc ice machine) collapses into a single vendor for most routine parts.
        Factory-direct parts still ship from Master-Bilt's New Albany, Mississippi plant, but the ordering runs through
        the Ali distributor network now, and in LA that usually means 3 to 5 business days to the truck. For parts the
        customer can't wait on, our techs install a compatible part from the truck and come back when the factory piece
        lands.
      </p>
      <p>
        Related sibling pages on this site cover the other Ali walk-in brands: <a href="/brands/kolpak-walk-in-repair/">Kolpak walk-in repair</a>
        and <a href="/brands/nor-lake-walk-in-repair/">Nor-Lake walk-in repair</a>. For an owner-operator who wants to stay
        out of the Ali Group parts network entirely, we also service <a href="/brands/us-cooler-walk-in-repair/">U.S. Cooler</a>
        — the independent alternative, oldest American walk-in manufacturer, still in Quincy, Illinois.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- LA ICE CREAM / PALETERIAS -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap narrow">
      <h2>LA ice-cream shops and Mexican paleterias — the DD cabinet niche</h2>
      <p>
        A decent percentage of our Master-Bilt call volume isn't walk-ins at all — it's DD-series dipping cabinets at
        ice-cream shops and Mexican paleterias across the LA basin. The ice-cream shop cluster is real: Salt &amp; Straw,
        McConnell's, Sweet Rose Creamery, Coolhaus, Carmela, and a long tail of independents have all standardized on
        panel-style dipping cabinets, and Master-Bilt DDs show up in a meaningful share of those back-of-house setups.
        When a DD loses its compressor during a July heat wave, the shop is out of service until a tech shows up — we
        route those as same-day priorities.
      </p>
      <p>
        The Mexican paleteria and panaderia cluster is the other half. Boyle Heights, East LA, Huntington Park, Pacoima,
        and the southeast LA corridor have hundreds of small family-owned paleterias running DD cabinets, DC-series
        reach-in freezers, and the occasional walk-in at a larger operation. Our Spanish-speaking techs handle those
        calls routinely — a thermostat calibration conversation at a paleteria is a different service conversation than
        at a Westside high-end ice-cream shop, and we don't make the owner translate. Same diagnostic fee, same parts
        supply, same trucks.
      </p>
      <p>
        Studio commissaries are a third slice. Back-of-house kitchens at Sony, Warner, Disney, and Paramount all run
        Master-Bilt hardware somewhere — walk-ins for catering prep, DD cabinets on sound stages for cast and crew
        service, reach-in freezers for commissary storage. Those calls come through the facilities team and we're on
        the approved-vendor list for most of the lot operations.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

